<TEXT>
victor bisio doesnt consider himself a fanatic 
about music even if he does own some 10000 albums and 2500 
compact discs 
but when he buys cds he expects them to live up to their 
original slogan perfect sound forever no pops no hisses 
no scratches music that brings you right in the studio 
thats why bisios massive collection includes a credit slip 
good for three albums from columbia records the slip arrived last 
summer a few months after he had purchased cds of barbra 
streisands first three records 
there had been mention from columbia that they couldnt find 
the original tapes but they put out the cds anyway said bisio a 
recording engineer who lives in encino calif they were are the 
worst sounding cds i ever heard they were screechy and distorted 
when she hit the high notes it just shattered your speakers 
compact discs arrived in the mid1980s and pushed lps out of 
stores since then bisio and other collectors have spent long 
hours comparing notes and keeping the pressure on record companies 
phil cohen a florida collector who owns over 6000 records 
bought the cd of jimi hendrixs electric ladyland three times 
before he found a satisfactory copy background noise made some 
tracks on james taylors sweet baby james virtually 
unlistenable for another collector 
collectors blame cd problems on laziness and greed insisting 
records made from inferior tapes were rushed onto the market and 
that songs were shortened or eliminated to fit albums on single 
discs the record companies admit mistakes but say some problems 
were unavoidable in switching from lps to cds 
in the beginning at least for the people who were asked to 
handle it it took a little bit more understanding of technology 
than to just say pull this tape and have it mastered said 
bill levinson director of catalog development at polygram records 
we had a handful of records eric claptons 461 ocean 
boulevard that were just not done from correct tapes the 461 
record was bad enough that we put out a new one and i told people 
in the press that we had done it 
among the worst cds 
fleetwood macs rumours a multiplatinum record originally 
released in the mid1970s it was pressed by warner bros records a 
decade later from an old production tape and the result was a 
muffled badly distorted cd a dramatically improved version was 
later released 
the jefferson airplanes after bathing at baxters was 
released in such poor condition that rca records apologized 
remastered the tape and offered an exchange 
collectors also had complaints about albums by elton john simon 
and garfunkel boz scaggs jimmy buffett carly simon and yes 
harry chapins verities and balderdash come without the booklet 
of photos and lyrics that was included on the lp gordon 
lightfoots gords gold was minus a song available on the lp 
there are some companies where no one in the music department 
makes the decision levinson said someone at the managerial 
desk says these next six ones are for reissue because the 
computer says these are the ones to go maybe theyre good maybe 
theyre not 
artists are beginning to take an active interest john arrias 
streisands personal engineer put together remastered versions of 
her first three records which have not yet been released 
guitarist jimmy page was so unhappy with the condition of several 
led zeppelin cds released by atlantic records he went back to the 
studio and helped produce a box set the bee gees consulted with 
polygram on a recent anthology which collectors say is very good 
and columbia which received the most criticism from collectors 
started columbialegacy records this year legacy has already put 
out wellreceived box sets of blues great robert johnson and the 
byrds made with the assistance of former band member roger 
mcguinn 
rich bauer product manager of catalog reissues at legacy said 
he hoped the problems were behind them 
when you try to put together a package from a record thats 
2025 years old it can be difficult to do everything as well as it 
can be done he said there are some records that havent come 
out such as the first two jeff beck records because of problems 
finding the original tapes 
polygram one of the first companies to set up its own domestic 
plant for producing cds received the most praise from collectors 
rhino records is also well regarded especially since its an 
independent label and needs permission from other companies to 
acquire master tapes 
we put out a compilation of hits of the 1970s and it was 
difficult explained gary stewart vice president of aampr artist 
and repertoire at rhino major labels are very professional 
good to deal with but for independent sources we have a hard time 
tracking them down and making deals especially companies no longer 
in the music business 
cds are digitally mastered as opposed to analog for lps a 
concept first tested in france in the 1920s digital is thought to 
produce a cleaner sound with less noise and distortion than 
analog 
digital recordings also known as pcm or pulse code modulation 
were first demonstrated in the late 60s and became available to 
the general public in 1972 when denon released the mozart hunting 
suite by the smetana quartet 
pcm recordings were only available on vinyl and cassette until 
the 80s when they were issued in the form of a 5inch compact 
disc developed by sony and philips 
collectors have few complaints about new albums but records 
made more than 10 years ago create problems companies may have a 
hard time tracking down the original master and end up using a 
second or thirdgeneration tape also technology has advanced so 
rapidly that recreating sounds produced on old equipment can 
require drastic measures 
i recently completed several classical records released in the 
1950s and 1960s said dennis drake polygrams vice president of 
studio and technical operations to transfer this catalog to cd 
we had to reconstruct the original machines a tube tape recorder 
and tube console these machines playing back the masters gave us 
the exact sound of the original recordings 
collectors hope the worst is over 
pete howard publisher and editor of international cd exchange 
ice a monthly newsletter that reviews compact discs notes that 
letters he receives these days deal more with minor compliants 
song length lyrics etc 
still hard feelings remain collectors have asked record 
companies to drop the price of cds not made from the original 
masters and to label discs to inform the customer whether theyve 
been remastered from an earlier version 
but the sticker could mean different things said polygrams 
levinson the implication of remastering could mean the previous 
one was no good or the previous one might have been good and 
youre making it better 
i also wouldnt want to have to put it in the artwork all the 
time it costs more to do that than to do remastering its a 
tough issue of balancing information and consumer needs sometimes 
the consumer thinks he deserves more than we can give 
</TEXT>
