<DOCNO> AP901219-0009 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
albert einstein called it the biggest blunder of 
his life but scientists said today that an idea he presented in 
1917 about the universe may have been right after all 
einstein came up with the cosmological constant to fix a 
problem his general relativity theory clashed with his belief that 
the size of the universe was unchanging 
the constant was a mathematical term that implied that the 
universe contains a repulsive force that acts against gravity when 
einstein added it to an equation describing his relativity theory 
the equation predicted a constantsize universe 
but scientists later showed that the universe was actually 
expanding the cosmological constant fell out of favor 
the late physicist george gamow in his autobiography my world 
line wrote that einstein told him that introducing the 
cosmological constant was the biggest blunder he ever made in his 
life 
but there might be something to it after all british scientists 
suggest in todays issue of the british journal nature 
george efstathiou william sutherland and steve maddox of the 
physics department at the university of oxford argue that the 
existence of the force represented by the cosmological constant 
would solve several problems with a standard theory about the 
universe it should be taken seriously they say 
the standard theory includes the big bang that gave birth to the 
universe and says that by far most of the mass in existence now is 
unobserved stuff called cold dark matter that would have a 
gravitational effect on the rest of the universe 
recent observations show more clustering of galaxies on very 
large scales than basic versions of the standard theory predict 
the new report says but the clustering could be accounted for by 
incorporating the force described by the cosmological constant into 
the standard theory the scientists propose 
their hypothesis suggests that the expansion of the universe was 
dominated by cold dark matter through perhaps the first onethird 
to onehalf of the history of the universe but that the 
cosmological constant force governs it now sutherland said in a 
telephone interview 
the hypothesis also accounts for the uniform intensity of the 
energy left over from the big bang and a number of distant 
galaxies that are difficult to fit into the volume of space 
allotted them by the standard theory sutherland said 
its still very speculative sutherland said i certainly 
would not like to claim that the cosmological constant is 
definitely there its a longshot but its a possiblity that we 
have to take seriously 
in a nature editorial theoretical astrophysicist edmund 
bertschinger of the massachusetts institute of technology said the 
new report may be the strongest case to date for a nonzero 
cosmological constant 
still he said in an interview the new evidence would not 
convince a jury i think beyond a reasonable doubt there are 
other possible explanations for the clustering of galaxies he 
said 
but the new work will promote debate and scientists will 
start to consider more seriously the consequences of having a 
cosmological constant he said 
for einstein of course it comes too late 
he missed a golden opportunity bertschinger said he 
could have predicted on the basis of his theory that the universe 
must be either expanding or contracting but he didnt trust the 
theory enough to do that 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

