<DOCNO> AP901219-0010 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
nehama beneliahu is one of the few israelis 
still willing to brave the hawkish trend in public opinion and turn 
out for street protests against military rule in the occupied 
territories 
but she also is lending her son money to buy a gun so that he 
feels safe from palestinians who could threaten his isolated farm 
near the west bank 
her situation illustrates the new dilemma of the doves in 
israel how to reconcile their calls for peace with the arabs with 
new fears of random attacks against jews 
the dilemma has been heightened by a recent rash of palestinian 
stabbing attacks on israelis and also by iraqi threats to attack 
the jewish state 
the result is that israels peace movement usually active in 
times of stress has grown unusually quiet 
there is a lot of confusion and worry we have tried to build 
bridges and now a volcano has come said aryeh eliav a leading 
activist in the leftofcenter labor party 
meetings between israeli and palestinian activists once common 
and public are now held either behind closed doors or not at all 
only 1000 activists attended a candlelight peace vigil staged 
outside prime minister yitzhak shamirs residence for the recent 
thirdyear anniversary of the palestinian uprising 
at the outset of the revolt such israeli peace protests 
routinely drew crowds exceeding 10000 but that was when 
consciences were guilty over soldiers shooting at youthful 
stonethrowing demonstrators 
now that the arabs are attacking israeli civilians sentiments 
are different 
earlier calls for jewisharab coexistence have been replaced by 
a new battle cry of separation recreating the old green line 
dividing israel from the west bank and gaza strip 
the persian gulf crisis also has undermined the peace movement 
leftists can no longer argue that the israelipalestinian conflict 
is at the heart of middle east instability and the palestinian 
question for the time being has been removed from the top of 
the united states agenda 
nobody wants to be active because they dont see where it will 
get them said nahum barnea a political analyst and leftleaning 
columnist for the yediot ahronoth daily 
public opinion surveys show israelis taking a hawkish turn 
pollster hanoch smith said a harsher attitude is permeating the 
entire societythe impact of the events is a tougher line he 
said in an interview 
at the same time however the growing violence is challenging 
rightwing beliefs that israel can annex the territories captured 
in the 1967 middle east war home to 17 million palestinians 
the effect in many cases has been an unexpected meeting of the 
minds between right and left on the need to separate the 
palestinian and jewish populations 
nowadays almost everyone left and right wants separation 
barnea said the jew has never so feared the lone arab working in 
his neighborhood 
the shared mood has legislators michael eitan of the rightwing 
likud bloc and gad yaacobi of leftleaning labor cooperating to 
draw up a plan for gradually separating the economies of the west 
bank and gaza strip from israel 
but yosef lapid a rightwinger noted in the daily maariv that 
a more common reaction to the violence is an allpervasive gloom 
despair has invaded israeli society it eats away at us he 
wrote 
hawks consider it pointless to press their arguments and the 
doves believe that whether consciously or not there is no chance 
for dialogue with the palestinians lapid added 
through the uncertainty the women in black a grassroots 
organization born with the uprising remains the most visible 
vestige of the peace movement in israel 
mrs beneliahu is a member she and several hundred women line 
up in downtown jerusalem and a dozen other towns every friday 
wearing black dresses and holding placards that read end the 
occupation 
the key to their survival says organizer anat hoffman is that 
they appeal to the majority of israelis who are sick of the 
occupation 
we arent standing up for the palestinians we say the 
occupation is bad because of what it does to us it costs us 2 
million a day and is morally disastrous mrs hoffman said 
mrs beneliahu 55 who was born in new york city and is a 
zoologist at jerusalems hebrew university started demonstrating 
for peace after her 19yearold son lost a leg in the 1973 middle 
east war 
the palestinian uprising only reinforces her feelings she says 
there is no question that unless we reach a political solution 
there will be an escalation in violence 
but being a pacifist isnt so simple these days she adds 
noting the money she is loaning another son for a pistol you 
see these are our needs today it shouldnt be this way we 
would all just have a better chance if there were peace 
