finance ministry 
the 1990 military budget was the last passed by the sandinista 
government which waged a 10year battle against ussupported 
contra rebels mrs chamorro defeated the sandinistas in elections 
earlier this year and took office in april 
deputies debated the budget package late tuesday as government 
leaders lobbied lawmakers to change their vote and army leaders to 
accept some cuts as a compromise 
earlier tuesday about 150 recently retired military officers 
held a march in front of the assembly building to protest the 
budget cuts claiming up to 10000 officers would be fired if the 
assembly overrides mrs chamorros veto 
the demonstrators were among 5000 who retired under a generous 
program that has reduced the size of the armed forces from about 
100000 when mrs chamorro was inaugurated april 25 to less than 
29000 
but the retirement program would not cover officers fired 
because of budget cuts sandinista lawmakers say 
the 51 members of mrs chamorros 14party coalition and one 
independent legislator voted in favor of the larger military cuts 
last week if they stick together they would override mrs 
chamorros veto 
the 39 sandinista deputies dont have the majority needed to 
counter the progovernment bloc a budget needs 47 votes to pass 
under the plan opposed by mrs chamorro the 19 million taken 
from the military would be spread around to benefit 15 other 
ministries and government departments 
mrs chamorro has said that while she favors further reducing 
the armed forces we cant do it overnight 
i think this veto will serve so that the gentlemen deputies 
reconsider this matter in its true dimension and decide whether or 
not they will support mrs chamorro said minister of the 
presidency antonio lacayo 
lacayo last week also warned that drastic cuts in the armed 
forces budget would endanger the nations stability 
a final budget for 1991 must be approved by midnight thursday 
