<TEXT>
the prestigious newsmagazine der spiegels cover 
story has a common theme these days in germany but an unaccustomed 
main actor one of spiegels own reporters is suspected of spying 
for communist east germany 
this weeks spiegel published monday spent 13 pages examining 
the allegations against diethelm schroeder that surfaced last week 
in a television expose 
the hamburgbased news weekly left schroeders name on the 
roster of its berlin bureau but noted he was on leave 
spiegel showed the drubbing it took from other german 
publications a headline in the masscirculation daily bild asked 
if schroeder was a traitor a cartoon republished from the 
rheinische post showed a spiegel sleuth following a spys tracks 
in a circle that became spiegels own trail 
i have to live with this story schroeder said in a 
telephone interview denying he had worked for the east german 
secret service or done anybody any harm 
spiegel called the denial a halfconfession 
the 60yearold native of eastern germany a military specialist 
who worked in the associated press germanlanguage service for 
five years in the sixties said his spiegel colleagues had 
explained that they had done major stories on other spy allegations 
and now we have to write a story about you 
i think its correct schroeder said adding with a laugh 
i would have had more fun if it was another story i think 
last week ard television named schroeder as having worked from 
1964 to 1987 for the stasi as the nowdefunct east germanys 
ministry for state security is called 
prosecutors confirmed that schroeder was under investigation 
though there was no word on how serious a case he might face 
conviction for passing state secrets can bring life in prison 
while a lesser charge of passing information to a foreign espionage 
agency carries a maximum 10year prison term 
as germany works to clear up the decades of crossborder spying 
prosecutors have already issued 61 arrest warrants this year 
spiegel which grew up with postwar west germany has been 
hitting the espionage issue hard along with other issues facing 
newly united germany 
only a week earlier spiegel had a scoop revealing evidence that 
east germanys first and only noncommunist prime minister lothar 
de maiziere had a stasi past de maiziere denies cooperating with 
secret police but quit as deputy head of the governing christian 
democratic union while prosecutors look into the evidence 
schroeder who remains free denies any wrongdoing telling 
spiegel he had had taken no money sent no written reports and hurt 
no one 
spiegels article wondered whether his denial might have been a 
halfconfession and asked through which activities was no 
one hurt 
doing the cover story was difficult said wolfram bickerich a 
senior editor in hamburg who had been friends with schroeder 
through working together 16 years 
but it was the only decision we could make because we said if 
we have such a case in our own house we are obliged to do this 
bickerich said in a telephone interview 
the cover story quoted schroeder as saying the allegations were 
a conspiracy against me or probably even against der spiegel 
it said three former stasi officials had revealed details about 
schroeders purported services for east german intelligence 
but the magazine cast doubt on the claim in the television 
program that schroeder had given the east germans valuable material 
on west german and nato defense planning and equipment 
the affable reporter was on close terms with the current nato 
secretarygeneral manfred woerner a former german defense 
minister schroeder was the first reporter to fly in a tornado 
fighterbomber he knew about scandals in west german officialdom 
schroeder came from the baltic coastal region that fell under 
soviet occupation and became east germany after world war ii he 
was trained as a journalist under the communist system but moved to 
west germany in 1956 his own story is that the soviet suppression 
of revolt in hungary caused him to abandon the east the allegation 
is that he was slipped into the west as a budding spy 
in his late 20s he worked for west german newspapers and then 
for aps german news service in frankfurt and bonn from 1960 to 
1965 
he was questioned in 1964 on suspicion of espionage against 
american forces schroeder read out a memo issued then to 
subscribers of aps germanlanguage service saying a reporter had 
been questioned his home and desk had been searched and he had 
been set free because the interrogation yielded no reason for his 
arrest 
the memo did not name the suspected reporter partly because he 
had relatives living under soviet occupation 
asked in the telephone interview if he had worked for the stasi 
schroeder said no the answer is no 
the questions directed to him he added were from former 
times not from the last 20 years 
in 1965 schroeder went to work for the bild newspaper in bonn 
and moved to spiegels bonn bureau in 1974 
spiegel quoted the chief federal prosecutor alexander von 
stahl as saying proceedings also were under way against two 
western german journalists other than schroeder 
