<TEXT>
for five centuries spaniards emigrated to 
the four corners of the globe in search of new worlds gold or just 
a better life for their families 
today an economically solid democratic spain has become a 
magnet for new generations of immigrants fleeing poverty and 
deadend lives in countries from morocco to the philippines 
although the steady flow of immigrants over the past decade has 
not yet become overwhelming spanish officials are concerned about 
how the country will cope with the newcomers most of them illegal 
european economic community officials worry that spains loose 
border controls will encourage illegal aliens and help them pass 
into other western european countries 
they are part of europes greatest refugee migration since world 
war ii it became a tide sweeping from east to west after the 
communist regimes of the soviet bloc collapsed a year ago 
this week the government circulated copies of a report on 
immigration to opposition leaders prior to coming parliamentary 
debate 
the report proposes an annual quota on immigration tighter 
border controls and heavy fines for those employing illegal 
immigrants 
according to fernando puig de la bellacasa head of the interior 
ministrys domestic policy department immigration is a new 
phenomenon for spain 
we were an exporter of emigrants now were a country 
receiving immigrants he said were not used to it were not 
set up for it 
a year ago mulie jarju worked in a plaster factory as an 
illegal alien from west africa whose requests for work and 
residence permits were repeatedly denied by authorities 
today the 33yearold native of gambia is the star of a new 
spanish film about the lives of illegal african aliens and their 
encounters with racism and exploitation 
letters from alou won the top prize at the san sebastian 
