rapidly increasing immigration from eastern europe 
more than 1000 poles a week are arriving one said were 
extremely worried about the dimension this could take 
as a signatory of the 1951 geneva convention on refugees spain 
is obliged to receive foreigners who seek refuge for political 
reasons and see they are paid a stipend until their cases have been 
decided 
both government authorities and private relief agencies agree 
that most asylum seekers show up in spain for economic not 
political reasons 
but the snailpaced bureaucratic process of reviewing individual 
requests for asylum allows many immigrants to slip through the 
cracks and into the underground economy where they find jobs in 
construction garment sweatshops and in fields and orchards picking 
fruit and vegetables 
since the summer about 150 africans awaiting decisions on their 
asylum petitions have been sleeping in a madrid park or in 
abandoned buildings because no one will rent them rooms 
since coming to spain six years ago jarju has picked fruit 
carted junk sold trinkets and sewed shirts in an illegal 
sweatshop his experiences served as a basis for the film 
