<TEXT>
portauprince haiti ap the apparent choice of a leftist 
priest as haitis first democratically elected president may be a 
historical phenomenon but is not a complete surprise 
the poor multitudes that voted for the rev jeanbertrand 
aristide on sunday have traditionally found haven and inspiration 
in churches 
in the 37yearold aristide believers saw a prophet who could 
end the political murders torture and corruption perpetrated by a 
series of repressive dictatorships 
even people who lack electricity managed to have a batteryrun 
radio to tune in to his sermons broadcast on catholic radio 
throughout this mountainous caribbean nation of 5 million 
roman catholicism voodoo and protestant missionaries have 
played key roles throughout the turbulent 186year history of 
haiti the worlds first black republic 
but in recent history politically oriented leftist offshoots of 
catholicism had perhaps the greatest popular influence 
such sects blossomed during the late 1970s when haiti was ruled 
by the duvalier family at the time hundreds of young priests 
nuns and layworkers moved away from the traditional church forming 
grassroots organizations in slums and among the peasantry 
opposition parties were banned and haitis bishops either 
praised the dictatorship or were silent 
the people were beginning to see their bishops as authority 
figures and beginning in some cases to associate that authority 
with the authority of the hated regime wrote amy wilentz in her 
book the rainy season 
the new religious movement was called the parish of the poor 
or little church and stemmed from liberation theology which 
advocates that the church become politically active to improve the 
lot of the poor 
liberation theology was rapidly spreading in latin america and 
its adherents in haiti were speaking out against the violence and 
overwhelming poverty the nations people were enduring under the 
duvaliers 
in 1983 pope john paul ii visited haiti and admonished the 
nations rulers boosting the efforts of the little church 
the duvalierist regime enforced by a private militia of thugs 
called the tonton macoutes began in 1957 with the rise to power of 
the late papa doc francois duvalier 
it ended after mass protests forced his son jeanclaude 
duvalier into exile in france in 1986 
the opposition to duvalier was expressed in these churches 
said jeanclaude bajeaux a widely respected human rights activist 
it was a place where fears and anger toward the macoutes could be 
expressed 
it was largely inside the yellow st jeanbosco church located 
on the edge of a slum that the young fiery and charismatic 
aristide berated the regime in biblical terms 
aristide was a priest who used the poetic words of the bible 
to speak out against duvalier said laennec hurbon a caribbean 
religion expert and author 
he was a moses whose mission was to save these people from the 
devils the devils being the macoutes said bajeaux 
ordained a salesian priest in 1982 aristide was given at the 
beginning the goahead by the conservative order to battle against 
duvalier but as his congregation grew larger the salesians backed 
off their support 
in their view he was leaning too much to the left said 
hurbon 
in 1988 he was expelled from the order for preaching class 
struggle 
the crime of which i stand accused of is the crime of 
preaching food for all people aristide wrote in his book in 
the parish of the poor 
that is what the salesians and the haitian bishops and the 
vatican call politics he wrote 
many conservatives interpret liberation theologians efforts to 
organize the poor as marxism and us officials have privately 
expressed fears that aristide could try to turn haiti into another 
cuba 
for their part holdovers of the duvalier regime have vowed to 
prevent an ultracommunist from taking power 
