<TEXT>
children with dangerously high cholesterol wont 
necessarily have the problem later in life scientists reported 
today in a study they said casts doubt on the need for cholesterol 
screening of all youngsters 
the authors of the study in the journal of the american medical 
association said univeral cholesterol screening for children would 
be expensive and would fail to pinpoint which adults will continue 
to show high cholesterol levels 
in another study in todays journal researchers said that 
cholesterolreducing drugs that help unclog mens coronary arteries 
and reduce their risk of heart attack do the same for women as 
well 
previous studies excluded women because men run a far higher 
risk of coronary problems at earlier ages cholesterol kills by 
clogging the blood vessels with lesions a combination of fatty 
deposits and scar tissue 
there are lots of other risk factors besides cholesterol but 
one of the most important risk factors is high cholesterol and 
reversal of atherosclerosis can reduce the chances of a heart 
attack dr mary malloy coauthor of the study said in a 
telephone interview tuesday 
the study loked at 41 women and 31 men with atherosclerosis 
over several years subjects took bile acidbinding resin and 
niacin daily which along with dietary changes reduced their 
cholesterol levels an average of 381 percent 
after 26 months coronary artery lesions shrank more than 2 
percent among 22 women enrolled in the treatment 
the 19 other women whose cholesterol levels were reduced an 
average of 106 percent through diet changes and lessintensive 
drug treatments showed an average increase of slightly more than 1 
percent in coronary artery lesions 
the treatments effect on men in the study showed the same 
trends but did not result in a statistically significant 
difference among men the study concluded 
dr david blankenhorn of the university of southern california 
who was not involved in the study said doctors are less likely to 
prescribe cholesterolreducing medicines for women because the 
evidence on their effectiveness wasnt in 
in the other study the cholesterol levels of 2367 children 
between the ages of 8 and 18 in muscatine iowa were examined and 
their cholesterol levels were again measured between the ages of 20 
and 30 
seventyfive percent of the females and 56 percent of the males 
with high cholesterol as children were under the levels described 
as dangerous by the national cholesterol education program when 
tested as adults the study found 
childhood cholesterol levels are a poor predictor of high 
cholesterol levels in young adulthood and will be an even poorer 
predictor of coronary heart disease later in life said the 
studys authors william r clarke and dr ronald lauer of the 
university of iowa 
</TEXT>
