<TEXT>
dec 18 
los angeles daily news on the education secretary nominee 
lamar alexander president bushs choice to be the new education 
secretary is an outspoken education activist who gets results and 
thats exactly the kind of person the job requires 
as governor of tennessee from 1978 to 1986 alexander was a 
leader by no means a mere bandwagonhopper in the growing 
educational reform movement he came up with a package of 
significant improvements in tennessees schools including 
statewide merit pay for teachers before most other elected 
officials seemed ready even to acknowledge that the nations 
schools had severe problems in contrast to lauro f cavazos 
who resigned from the position alexander is a selfstarter 
who probably wont have to wait for cues from the white house to 
set an agenda for educational reform 
alexander compares favorably to cavazos in another way as well 
the former governor was effective in using his office to take on 
the teachers unions fellow republicans and others who didnt share 
his commitment to educational reform 
alexander will need to use these same political skills if he is 
to succeed in his new job the same establishment that fought his 
reforms in tennessee will be ready to jump down his throat in 
washington at the mere mention of such reform concepts as 
educational choice and a uniform national test for students 
 
dec 13 
roswell nm daily record on germany 
a year ago when the berlin wall had just been breached and 
germanys future was uncertain a great deal of concern was 
expressed around the globe about the prospects of a united more 
powerful germany the parliamentary elections held recently to 
choose a new allgerman government should allay most of those 
fears 
in the first free balloting throughout germany since november 
1932 the voters reaffirmed the sensible political middle 
chancellor helmut kohls christian democratic union was given a 
solid mandate to build on the policies that led to swift 
reunification 
significantly the voters in the east endorsed kohls vision in 
about the same ratio as the electorate in the west and kohls 
vision is one of a united germany firmly moored to the north 
atlantic treaty organization and the european community 
barely a year after the berlin wall was toppled germans have 
voted for a united nation tied economically and militarily to the 
western democracies the oncewidespread fears that german unity 
would wrack the continent with renewed conflict suddenly seem 
overblown 
 
dec 18 
arizona daily star tucson ariz on the persian gulf 
good red american blood is a renewable resource good rich 
crude oil is not 
because one represents life and the other represents the fuel 
that powers what has become the american way of life youd think 
both would be equally precious 
they are not 
the president who is willing to draw lines in the sand with 
american blood for the sake of saudi oil is unwilling to even 
discuss cutting down on domestic oil consumption 
energy secretary james watkins understands that a national 
energy policy without an energyconservation component is as 
useless as a ford without fuel 
thats why watkins built energy conservation into the proposal 
hes been working on for 18 months its also why the white house 
dinosaurs chief of staff john sununu chief economic adviser 
michael j boskin and budget director richard darman told watkins 
to drop conservation proposals from the national energy strategy 
the white house dinosaurs dont want an energy policy to go 
anywhere as minions of oil man george bush their goal is to 
preserve the status quo until every bit of money can be made out of 
every bit of oil on the face of the earth 
and if that takes every drop of good red american blood so be 
it 
the laissez faire attitude to energy conservation by the 
reaganbush administration assured that the united states would 
remain dependent on oil and heavily dependent on foreign oil 
 
dec 14 
the bulletin bend ore on the persian gulf 
former hostages who returned in the past few days from iraq and 
kuwait were almost universal in their praise of the way the bush 
administration has handled the gulf crisis 
bushs quickness to act his callup of military strength his 
clear warnings to saddam hussein and his successful grouping of an 
overpowering opposition all taken together made hussein realize he 
was on shaky ground 
releasing the hostages was his way of meeting at least one of 
the requirements bush laid down 
times were not easy for the hostages many of them spent four 
months in hiding many survived through the heroism of kuwaiti 
friends who hid and fed them 
but they might well have been there for years rather than 
months had bush not acted as strongly and decisively as he did 
almost universally the released hostages appear to realize that 
 
dec 14 
the providence ri journalbulletin on the persian gulf 
amid the happiness at the freeing of iraqs hostages we want to 
take special note of nathaniel howell the us ambassador to 
kuwait and his embassy staff during four months of hostile 
occupation surrounded and isolated by unpredictable iraqi troops 
ambassador howell retained his calm and kept the embassy 
functioning 
with war scares running high he and his skeleton staff of four 
other foreign service officers managed to make do for most of their 
enforced isolation on embassy stocks of canned tuna augmented by 
water from a swimming pool by firmly resisting the iraqi demands 
that he depart ambassador howell helped to legitimize kuwaits 
status as an independent state he and his staff handled a tough 
situation with real distinction 
 
</TEXT>
