dec 18 
sunsentinel fort lauderdale fla on sanctions 
south africa and iraq are as dissimilar as gold and oil yet the 
apparent importance of economic sanctions in bringing about 
substantive change in one country may have timely relevance to the 
other 
much of the world but principally the united states and the 
european community imposed a variety of sanctions on south africa 
during the 1980s as punishment for that nations adherence to a 
system of legal segregation known as apartheid 
now the international community is virtually united in an 
economic embargo and military blockade intended to compel iraq to 
withdraw from occupied kuwait 
while politicians debate the impact of the iraqi sanctions and 
ponder the wisdom of going to war to enforce the global will they 
could well draw an important lesson from recent developments in 
south africa 
 
dec 16 
the sunday telegraph london on the persian gulf 
any visible failure of american nerve in the persian gulf 
would mean the end of the present system of world security what 
could take its place 
instead of grappling with this urgent question europes leaders 
prefer to waste their time talking about european political union 
which is not only a profoundly divisive aspiration but also one 
that could not possibly be realized for many years to come 
for once the united nations should be the focus of attention 
every ounce of european diplomacy should be concentrated on 
steeling american resolve to carry out the un mandate in the 
gulf 
world security not european union is the question of the hour 
it is sad that there is now no longer a single european statesman 
with the courage to say so 
 
dec 17 
the times of india new delhi on the soviet union 
though outside reports about the soviet union being on the verge 
of collapse may well be exaggerated the country and its leader are 
facing the gravest crisis yet 
for the first time since mikhail gorbachev came to power the 
initiative seems to have shifted to the conservatives 
also for the first time key representatives of the army and the 
kgb are making major policy statemenets in public which are virtual 
warnings that the executive under gorbachev will have to move 
toward a major crackdown 
 
dec 17 
the sydney australia morning herald on south africa 
is the african national congress in danger of losing its grip on 
the antiapartheid struggle in south africa 
that cleavages within the anc should be opening up now is not 
all that surprising 
there is a generational gap between the current top leadership 
and most of its members there is a jostling for position and 
power 
there are inevitable differences of opinion over tactics over 
how much trust to place in president de klerk and over how much 
should be compromised in the interests of a lasting peace 
what is surprising is the time it has taken the anc to begin 
getting its house in order the delay has been costly it has 
allowed indiscipline to grow in the ranks of the anc and that in 
turn to feed the blackonblack violence in natal province 
it has increased the chances of impatience for reform cutting 
anc leaders off from younger more militant members of the 
organization it has played into the hands of whites inside and 
outside de klerks government who seek to portray the anc as 
incompetent and dangerous for south africa 
it is a luxury of time the anc can no longer afford 
 
dec 15 
the daily press ashland wis on tariff talks 
although there are several reasons why the depression of the 
1930s happened it is generally agreed that restrictive tariff wars 
contributed greatly 
today the united states is participating in the general 
agreement on tariffs and trade negotiations in brussels there has 
been a call among many politicians for the us to pull out of the 
negotiations that we are not receiving the kinds of assurances we 
need 
granted the doors are open wider for foreign products entering 
this country than they are for most we do pay a price when it 
comes to marketing our products worldwide but there are stronger 
reasons for us to remain a working partner in the tariff and trade 
agreements 
first levying tariffs on imported products quite simply fuels 
inflation many of the products in question will still be sold here 
to a willing public we will simply have to pay more 
but most important the us should not be party to a spiraling 
tariff war that eventually catches up with everybody prior to the 
depression the trading powers closed their doors to smaller 
nations thinking that we were immune to recessionary influences we 
were wrong 
promoting a world economy not only establishes a system 
versatile enough to withstand devastating depressions but also 
creates economic growth worldwide why is that important to us the 
world cant buy what we sell unless they have the money first 
 
</TEXT>
