<TEXT>
three warring factions and liberias 
west africansponsored interim government are to meet thursday to 
try to fashion a ceasefire and end one of africas bloodiest power 
struggles 
the talks are being held in banjul gambia they begin four days 
before the oneyear anniversary of the rebel invasion that ousted 
former president samuel doe and quickly evolved into a brutal 
tribal conflict 
during that time more than 12000 civilians have been 
slaughtered and over 750000 liberians have fled to neighboring 
west african nations about half of liberias 23 million people 
have been left homeless 
charles taylor a onetime government bureaucrat led the rebel 
effort that toppled doe whom he accused of gross corruption and 
brutal oppression 
since then taylors army the largest of the three warring 
factions has overrun most of liberia outside the capital 
monrovia 
many liberians accuse taylor of prolonging the bloodshed since 
followers of a breakaway rebel leader prince johnson allegedly 
killed doe in september after brutually torturing him 
the third faction is composed of doe loyalists 
the warring factions disagree over the composition of a 
temporary government to organize elections and on how to enforce a 
ceasefire agreed at a summit of west african leaders in bamako 
mali on nov 28 
an 8000man west african army composed of troops from gambia 
ghana sierra leone nigeria and guinea has been sent to monitor 
the ceasefire 
taylor has rejected the interim government set up by veteran 
politician amos sawyer with the backing of other west african 
nations he refused an offer of six seats on sawyers cabinet 
which includes four doe loyalists and four members of johnsons 
faction 
the interim government was appointed by a group of exiled 
liberians at an august meeting sponsored by the economic community 
of west african states a west african peace plan bans sawyer from 
contesting proposed 1991 general elections to ensure a fair 
outcome 
both johnson and the leader of the liberian army brig hezekiah 
bowen have accepted sawyers government 
taylor has set himself up as president of his own interim 
administration and has insisted the other factions join his 
government they have all rejected the demand 
it remains to be seen if taylor will be tempted by sawyers 
offer of more cabinet positions and legislative seats but his 
immediate future depends on the west african army put together to 
monitor the ceasefire 
taylor attacked the west african troops when they sailed into 
monrovia on aug 5 he agreed to stop fighting after the west 
africans retaliated pushing his men out of monrovias eastern 
suburbs and bombing his supply lines 
taylor questions the neutrality of the force which is commanded 
by a nigerian general and has 4000 nigerian troops nigerias 
president gen ibrahim babangida was a friend of does 
taylor has accused the west african force of siding with 
remnants of does army whom the west africans are in the process 
of relocating from barracks at the presidential mansion and a 
nearby garrison to a camp 15 miles outside the capital 
the move came after johnson broke the ceasefire on nov 30 and 
attacked the doe loyalists whom he and many monrovians accused of 
attacks on civilians the west african army responded by attacking 
johnsons force and the fighting ended two days later johnsons 
men now are confined to a camp at caldwell a town northeast of 
monrovia 
