<TEXT>
housing starts rose in november for the first 
time in 10 months but construction of singlefamily homes 
plummeted to a level not seen since the last recession the 
government said wednesday 
the declines in singlefamily starts and permits suggest we 
havent hit bottom yet and there may be further deterioration in 
the coming months said economist john a tuccillo of the 
national association of realtors 
thomas holloway an economist with the mortgage bankers 
association agreed but added the bottom is in sight and we see 
improvement in the spring of next year 
the commerce department said starts of new homes and apartments 
rose to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 113 million units 
advancing for the first time since a 232 percent gain in january 
but the advance was due solely to a 102 percent rebound in 
multifamily starts which had dropped 28 percent a month earlier 
multifamily starts totaled 357000 at an annual rate in november 
david g seiders an economist with the national association of 
home builders said the multifamily rate could not be sustained 
theres no way thats going to happen he said 
but he and other economists were hardpressed to explain the 
pickup 
the october level was too low and the november rate was too 
high robert sheehan an economist with the national apartment 
association said an average of the two levels at 267000 units 
is probably closer to the real trend 
economists attributed the continuing weakness in the 
singlefamily sector to steep inventories of unsold homes and 
consumer uncertainty over the economy and the persian gulf some 
also said that tight restrictions on credit were keeping marginal 
buyers out of the market 
builders are facing up to the demand side of the market and 
reacting to it seiders said 
applications for building permits often a barometer of future 
activity fell 14 percent to 907000 the lowest level since 
888000 forms were issued in april 1982 
until november housing starts had fallen for nine months in a 
row the first time that has happened since the government began 
keeping track of permits in 1959 during the first 11 months of the 
year starts were down 128 percent from the same period of 1989 
construction of singlefamily units totaled a seasonally 
adjusted annual rate of 772000 down from 856000 in october it 
was the lowest level since 737000 units were started in october 
1982 
the multifamily activity was led by a rebound in buildings 
containing five or more units up 1013 percent to 314000 units 
these units had declined 268 percent in october 
housing starts rose 213 percent to 478000 units in the south 
and 54 percent to 274000 in the west 
but they were down 14 percent to 140000 units in the 
northeast which has seen some of the slowest housing activity in 
recent months 
starts were unchanged at 237000 units in the midwest 
