<TEXT>
the bush administration has dropped its 
opposition to a plan by american telephone amp telegraph co to 
provide additional phone service to the soviet union through an 
east bloc satellite consortium 
atampt citing a 140 percent increase in ussoviet phone traffic 
from 1987 through 1989 began seeking federal permission 12 months 
ago to provide about 100 additional phone circuits to the soviet 
union through the intersputnik system 
the state department said in may that it saw no reason to 
deviate from existing us policy that requires most satellite 
telephone traffic between the two countries to be carried by the 
119nation intelsat satellite cooperative 
however deputy secretary of state lawrence s eagleburger and 
deputy secretary of commerce thomas j murrin reversed course in a 
dec 14 letter to federal communications commission chairman alfred 
sikes 
the officials said the modest nature of the atampt proposal 
alleviated us concern that intelsat would suffer from the 
competing service 
the administration views this action as an important step in 
promoting business development and commerce between the united 
states and the soviet union the state department said in a 
prepared statement 
atampt spokesman herb linnen said the company was pleased with the 
administrations change of heart 
atampt has about 60 circuits to the soviet union by means of 
intelsat undersea cables and land lines atampt uses about 22000 
intelsat circuits worldwide 
the company said demand for phone calls to the soviet union was 
far exceeding atampts ability to carry them and proposed splitting 
future circuit increases between intelsat intersputnik and 
undersea cables 
atampt had sought permission from the fcc to build a new satellite 
antenna at atampts roaring creek earth station near catawissa pa 
to transmit calls to an intersputnik satellite above the west coast 
of africa the fcc has not acted on the application 
atampt said the soviet union preferred to use its own satellite 
system for additional phone circuits because moscow then incurs 
expenses solely within the soviet union payable in rubles rather 
than in western currencies 
rubles are not traded officially in international money markets 
intersputnik is a consortium of 15 formerly communist countries 
that provides satellitedelivered communications among its member 
nations 
</TEXT>
