german unification could raise interest rates 
in the united states by at least a full percentage point after 
1992 a congressional study released wednesday said 
the congressional joint economic committee which requested the 
study said in a statement that if germany finances higher 
government spending with higher borrowing real shortterm interest 
rates are estimated to be a full percentage point higher in the 
1990s in the united states 
the study by the congressional budget office projected that 
the interest rate hike in the united states could be 06 percent 
next year 09 percent by 1992 1 percent by 1993 and 11 percent 
by 1994 
the study said that if the german government helps its new 
eastern states with tax money there would be little international 
effect but chancellor helmut kohl recently won the first election 
since unification after a promise not to raise taxes higher taxes 
would replace higher borrowing 
the committee said that much of the money the united states 
borrows comes from the savings of germans that borrowed money goes 
to cover the deficit in the federal budget and to pay for imports 
if the german government borrows more of its peoples savings for 
its own purposes interest rates could rise in both countries 
german government borrowing could have other effects too the 
study said it found that in 1992 it could cause a small drop in 
american production and a potential increase in us exports of 
159 billion 
the report pointed out that the reduction of the military threat 
from eastern europe could save the united states money on defense 
but did not offer a figure the study did not cover the soviet 
union itself 
the transformation of eastern europe should have its most 
significant impact on the us economy in two ways by slightly 
raising us interest rates and by enabling lower defense 
expenditures a peace dividend arising from the end of the cold 
war the study said 
exports to eastern europe could increase by as much as 6 
billion in 1994 it estimated 
