<TEXT>
breast cancers may recruit normal tissue to help 
launch their invasion of other parts of the body a discovery that 
may open a new target for therapy a study suggests 
scientists identified a gene that is activated in normal cells 
surrounding invasive breast cancers spurring the normal cells to 
produce an enzyme that may help cancer cells spread from the 
original tumor 
the makeup of the gene suggests that this enzyme may degrade 
normal tissue surrounding a tumor creating pathways for the cancer 
cells to escape scientists reported in thursdays issue of the 
british journal nature 
the enzyme which the scientists dubbed stromelysin3 is 
produced by stromal cells which make up supporting structure 
within breasts the scientists said 
apparently breast cancers produce some kind of substance that 
activates the stromal cells to produce the enzyme they suggested 
the enzyme may be a new target for cancer therapy they said 
the work was reported by pierre chambon and colleagues at the 
institute of biological chemistry of the national institute of 
medical research in strasbourg france 
dr lance liotta a national cancer institute expert on how 
cancer spreads said it was unclear what the discovery means for 
cancer treatment for one thing nobody knows whether the enzyme 
really helps cancers spread or whether it provides a defense he 
said wednesday 
liotta said scientists had previously identified other enzymes 
that help cancers spread by destroying tissue these substances are 
created by cancer cells themselves he said 
</TEXT>
