institutions dropped from 505000 in 1955 to less than 118000 
today and that many of these people with no place to go were 
sentenced to americas streets grates doorways and park 
benches 
he said the federal budget for subsidized lowincome housing has 
trickled down to almost nothing over the past decade another 
reason more people are without homes 
the federal government has walked away now with the states 
downturn in their economies they are walking away so the cities 
are getting a doublewhammy the cities are dealing with the 
problem alone 
we havent dealt with the basic social problems in this 
country for a long time myrick said anything we do in putting 
money into homeless shelters is a bandaid approach 
eightyseven percent of the cities used locally generated 
revenues to finance aid to the homeless ranging from 26000 in 
new orleans to 131 million in new york all accepted federal funds 
from the mckinney homeless assistance act going from 23000 in 
san juan to 36 million in new york 
