<TEXT>
nasa has lost the glamour that once attracted 
top people to its ranks and the agency is now not competitive with 
industry and academia in hiring of the best and brightest 
according to a federal report released wednesday 
contrary to the popular saying at nasa you do have to be a 
rocket scientist to fill many of its demanding positions said 
the final full report of the advisory committee on the future of 
the us space program 
the study said that the excitement of working for nasa has faded 
and that the space agency in its hiring now is not competitive 
for experienced engineers and senior technicallyqualified 
managers 
but to get such people nasa now loses out to worldclass 
industrial and academic institutions seeking the same sort of 
talent the report said 
in the past the challenge and excitement of the space program 
has been a significant inducement for exactly the type of people 
one wishes to attract said the report recently however it 
said criticism of the space program and its participants and the 
image of public service in general have made nasa a less 
attractive employer 
because of these problems the committee said it was not 
confident that in the future nasa will be able to obtain or 
retain the necessary cadre of skilled personnel in a field where 
the most critical asset is the talent of the individual 
participants 
the 12member advisory committee was appointed four months ago 
to study the civil space program and to make recommendations to 
vice president dan quayle and to nasa administrator richard truly 
a summary of the report was released last week the full report was 
issued wednesday 
to help nasa attract special skills the committee called for 
reforms in civil service regulations that would allow the agency to 
pay higher salaries for specific skills and to give more 
flexibility in establishing pay schedules in certain circumstances 
among the other recommendations of the committee were 
reduce reliance on the space shuttle and the development of 
new unmanned launch vehicles to put satellites and other equipment 
into orbit 
redesign space station freedom with a goal of reducing costs 
and complexity the space station mission the committee said 
should center on life sciences and human space operations and less 
on industrial process research 
science should be given the highest priority in the space 
program and science activities should be maintained at or above 20 
percent of the nasa budget 
nasa should not build a fifth space shuttle but keep the fleet 
at four after the new orbiter endeavour is delivered next year 
a longterm program should be established to carry out president 
bushs goal of establishing a permanent base on the moon and the 
human exploration of the planet mars along with an effort to 
produce significant advances in space transportation and life 
sciences 
bush has said he wanted the mars landing by 2019 but the 
committee said the schedule should be designed to match the 
availability of federal funds 
a project to study the planet earth from orbit should be 
initiated and continued over several decades rather than a 
mission whose design is frozen in time 
