the worst outbreak of st louis 
encephalitis in florida since 1962 is over state health officials 
said wednesday nine people died from the disease 
the onset of cooler weather cut the numbers of mosquitos that 
carry the disease leading the state department of health and 
rehabilitative services to pronounce the end of the outbreak 
we just havent had any cases in four weeks the mosquito 
count is nil so it was the right time to call it off said 
health agency spokesman david adams 
in addition to the deaths 202 people were infected with the 
virus and thousands more were forced to curtail nighttime 
activities ranging from high school football to halloween 
trickortreat 
the encephalitis outbreak also frightened tourists and put a 
scare into merchants worried about its impact on the economy cases 
were reported in 27 counties on both coasts stretching from 
jacksonville to miami 
state health officials said outbreaks of st louis encephalitis 
run in cycles of five to 10 years with only about five cases 
reported during a normal year in the 1962 outbreak 222 cases were 
reported 
the outbreaks are tied to increases in the population of the 
culex nigrapalpus mosquito which draws the disease from the blood 
of migrating birds the viral infection causes inflammation of the 
brain 
