<TEXT>
the un childrens fund on wednesday 
urged world leaders to make good on a recent pledge to help prevent 
millions of child deaths from hunger and disease this decade 
james p grant unicefs executive director who issued the 
report titled the state of the worlds children said the 
world has never before undertaken such a global commitment as it 
did for children in 1990 
seventyone presidents kings and prime ministers joined envoys 
of 88 other nations at the united nations on sept 19 the largest 
such gathering in history to pledge a redoubled effort to save 
children 
the summit set 20 goals for the year 2000 including a onethird 
reduction in child deaths a halving of child malnutrition and the 
introduction of basic schooling for at least 80 percent of the 
developing worlds children 
an estimated 40000 child die daily from sickness and 
malnutrition another estimated 150 million children worldwide lack 
proper health care and 100 million children aged 6 to 11 do not 
attend school the report said 
the declarations of political leaders are not enough the 
goals for the year 2000 must become the goals of society as a 
whole grant said 
the report urged nations to reexamine national spending 
priorities and public policies by no later than the end of 
1991 
while the cost of fulfilling the summit goals by 2000 will 
require roughly 20 billion a year much of that figure can be 
achieved by a reallocation of resources the report said 
it suggested a small reduction in military expenditures debt 
relief linked to investments in children and a reallocation of 
funds from highcost services to lowcost items such as vaccines 
with the ending of the cold war and the easing of regional 
tensions it cannot be too unrealistic to suggest a 5 percent cut 
in defense spending which would liberate half of the estimated 
20 billion a year needed to reach the year 2000 goals the 
report argued 
at present the report noted only about 3 percent of the 
industrialized worlds aid is devoted to such basics as primary 
education and primary health care 
but unicef said its goals are achievable one of its last 
10year goals the immunization of nearly 80 percent of the 
developing worlds children by 1990 has been virtually reached up 
from 15 percent immunization in 1980 
that extraordinary achievement unicef said has not only 
saved 12 million young lives it has also given the world new hope 
by showing what can be achieved when the international community 
commits itself to a great endeavor 
