<TEXT>
casual use of cocaine the most virulent drug 
of the 1980s has fallen 72 percent in the last five years the 
government said in a report issued wednesday 
the magnitude of the progress is impressive indeed 
president bush said at a news conference releasing the household 
survey on drug abuse the news we have today suggests that our 
hard work is paying off and our national strategy is having an 
effect 
but critics including sen joseph r biden jr took issue with 
the survey biden ddel said it misses more addicts than it 
counts 
not all the news was positive 
the survey reported a continuing of a trend found two years ago 
the number of people who used cocaine daily or almost daily rose by 
37 percent over five years from 246000 in 1985 to 336000 this 
year 
in addition the number of current crack cocaine users remained 
stable at about a halfmillion nida director charles r schuster 
said the survey undercounts such users 
bush said its too early to declare a victory despite the 
findings that drug use in general is down 
as long as there are hospital rooms filled with drugaffected 
babies neighborhoods ravaged by drug violence or children 
threatened by addiction a declaration of victory would be 
premature bush said 
about 129 million people 64 percent of the population age 12 
and older are current users also known as casual users 
meaning they use some kind of illicit drug at least once a month 
according to the survey sponsored by the national institute on drug 
abuse 
thats 44 percent fewer than the 23 million in 1985 an 11 
percent decline from the 145 million two years ago 
for current cocaine use the decline was even more dramatic 
down 72 percent from 58 million in 1985 to 16 million this year 
since 1988 the number dropped 45 percent from 29 million 
the survey did not specify how much of a drug was used only how 
frequently it was used 
on capitol hill biden said a study by his senate judiciary 
committee estimates about 24 million people use cocaine at least 
once a week not the 662000 cited in the household survey 
and the committee report says the number of such hardcore 
cocaine users has increased by 200000 rather than declining by 
that number as the nida survey indicated 
rep charles rangel dny chairman of house select committee 
on narcotics abuse and control said he believes drug use is 
dropping among those who are best equipped to avoid the lure of 
drugs 
however i do not think that drug use has decreased among 
those who are a part of the populations that are homeless in 
prison in hospitals receiving treatment for aids and other 
drugrelated illnesses or similar groups located in our inner 
cities rangel said 
administration officials acknowledged that the household survey 
misses homeless people as well as those in prison shelters 
drugtreatment centers and other institutions such as dormitories 
they also said 18 percent of the households contacted declined to 
participate 
schuster estimated that as many as 50 percent of the more than 1 
million people imprisoned nationwide are drug users 
but dr james o mason assistant secretary for health said the 
surveys tracking of trends if not the precise numbers of users 
is accurate because the survey has been administered the same way 
all 10 times since 1971 he also said the findings are similar to 
those of other studies 
its evident the survey misses many drug users 
for example it estimates thre are 48000 current users of 
heroin when nida has been saying for the past decade that there are 
about 500000 heroin addicts people who use the drug far more 
often than once a month 
among the surveys findings based on interviews this year with 
9259 people age 12 and over 
the number of adolescents using any illicit drugs dropped in 
the past two years by 13 percent from 19 million to 16 million 
for cocaine the number dropped 49 percent from 225000 to 
115000 
emergency rooms are seeing fewer cocainerelated cases the 
number decreased 95 percent from the first quarter to the second 
quarter of 1990 its down 33 percent from the highest levels 
recorded in the fourth quarter of 1988 and the second quarter of 
1989 
heroinrelated emergency room cases dropped 18 percent from the 
second quarter of 1988 to the second quarter of 1990 about the 
same decrease experienced for all drugrelated emergency room 
visits combined 
marijuana remains the most commonly used illicit drug even 
though the number of current users has declined 43 percent in the 
last five years from 18 million in 1985 to 102 million this year 
the number of people who drink alcoholic beverages weekly 
declined 24 percent over five years from 546 million in 1985 to 
417 million this year 
current cigarette users declined 111 percent from 603 
million in 1985 to 536 million this year 
louis w sullivan secretary of the department of health and 
human services said the survey results must be greeted with 
guarded optimism 
there are still millions of americans trapped in the web of 
addiction poor health violence crime and death he said 
despite this impressive good news about our progress many 
pockets of serious drug problems remain 
