<TEXT>
portauprince haiti ap five years after the fall of the 
duvalier family dictatorship haitians have finally chosen a 
president in this impoverished caribbean nations first fully 
democratic election 
now the probable winner the rev jeanbertrand aristide faces 
the job of carrying out his pledge to wash away the duvalier legacy 
of repression corruption and government neglect 
that legacy includes an army notorious for its human rights 
abuses an ineffectual judicial system a population with a 65 
percent illiteracy rate and a per capita income of 360 a year 
the danger for aristide a charismatic priest with huge popular 
support but virtually no government experience is that he may be 
unable to satisfy the high expectations he has raised among the 
haitis poor 
they hope he will bring better living conditions and an end to 
totalitarian rule 
three days after sundays election only 153 percent of the 
official results had been announced but they gave aristide an 
overwhelming 65 percent of the vote in line with the outcome 
projected by international observers 
the priests nearest competitor among the 10 other candidates 
former world bank official marc bazin regarded as the bush 
administrations favorite was a distant second with 115 percent 
of the vote 
aristide will ask opposition parties to form an alliance with 
his new government his major adviser evans paul said wednesday 
paul coleader with aristide of the coalition national front for 
democracy and change said they would especially seek out the 
centerright national industrial and agricultural party led by 
louis dejoie jr who drew 27267 votes or 84 percent 
jeanclaude bajeaux a prominent human rights activist 
attributed aristides apparent landslide win to his fight against 
duvalierists who have gone unpunished for the atrocities of the 
29year dictatorship 
aristide is the medium through which the people have 
discovered the possibility of being protected by being together 
bajeaux said thats what the other haitian politicians didnt 
understand the people wanted justice 
aristide 37 has been the target of several assassination 
attempts including a 1988 attack at his former church in which at 
least 12 of his parishioners were murdered and 70 wounded 
in the only violence of the election campaign terrorists hurled 
a grenade and fired bullets into an aristide rally on dec 5 
killing seven and wounding more than 50 others 
with the victory of aristide the people have taken back feb 
7 1986 which the duvalierists stole said bus driver pierre 
merveille 44 
on that day jeanclaude baby doc duvalier fled to france 
after a popular uprising ending the dynasty found by his late 
father francois papa doc in 1957 haitians celebrated then 
expecting broad change instead they have seen five governments 
four controlled by the army 
because aristide is so closely identified with the struggle 
against tyranny haitians may be expecting more of him than they 
would from an establishment politician but his popularity with the 
impoverished masses ironically may be his achilles heel 
dr louis roy president of the interim goverments advisory 
council of state and principal author of the 1987 constitution 
said aristide must move swiftly to make changes 
within his oneyear grace period he must take the first 
spectacular steps to show he intends to strengthen public finances 
the judicial system and provide essential social services 
roy said 
but aristide risks a backlash from such traditional powers as 
the military and the wealthy elite if he clamps down too hard and 
too fast said anne fuller associate director of the new 
yorkbased national coalition for haitian refugees who was in 
haiti to observe the election 
my feeling is that hes not going to act very quickly on these 
things she said 
aristide adheres to liberation theology which encourages the 
poor to demand their rights he was expelled from his conservative 
salesian order in 1988 for allegedly fomenting revolution 
he remains a roman catholic priest but has said he will renounce 
his calling if the vatican imposes its policy against holding 
political office 
his leftist philosophy has raised concern among the business 
establishment and the bush administration but the us government 
has pledged support for the democratic transition which is 
expected to result in a resumption of largescale foreign aid 
robert pastor latin america specialist at the carter center in 
atlanta who also observed the election said he thought a critical 
decision for aristide will be the appointment of a prime minister 
with sound administrative experience 
bazin has been mentioned but the onetime finance minister and 
aristide are at opposite political poles and paul said on wednesday 
there is no possibility aristide would ask bazin to be prime 
minister 
the army has pledged support for the transition to democracy 
but the intentions of duvalier sympathizers within remain unclear 
about 800 international observers including former president 
jimmy carter were on hand for the election millions of dollars in 
foreign aid poured in for voting materials and equipment 
despite serious delays at some polling stations due to 
logistical problems the observers unanimously declared the 
election open fair and peaceful 
 
</TEXT>
