<TEXT>
a federal judge approved a settlement 
wednesday with the government that stalls deportation of thousands 
of salvadoran and guatemalan refugees denied political asylum 
settlement of a 1985 civil lawsuit on behalf of about 80 
sanctuary assistance organizations was signed by us district 
judge robert peckham 
the agreement was supported by the justice department but is 
subject to a final approval hearing jan 31 in san francisco 
the settlement applies to every salvadoran and guatemalan in 
the united states who has been denied asylum since 1980 frand 
deale legal director of the center for constitutional rights said 
in a statement from new york 
the settlement calls for new deportation hearings for thousands 
of refugees 
as many as 150000 denials will have to be readjudicated and 
up to 500000 salvadoran and guatemalans will be affected by the 
settlement deale said 
we think it is a fair agreement but well make no further 
statement justice department spokesman joe krovisky said 
years of legal wrangling included peckhams rebuff of government 
attempts to dismiss the lawsuit peckham rejected government 
arguments that the lawsuit depended on foreign policy questions 
outside the courts authority 
the case was handled by deales center the national lawyers 
guild the americal civil liberties union and the san francisco law 
firm morrison and forrester 
the lawsuit claiming discrimination contended the government 
was violating its own immigration laws by rejecting nearly all 
requests for political asylum from natives of the two central 
american countries 
it said despite civil strife in those countries only 3 percent 
of salvadorans and less than 1 percent of guatemalans were granted 
asylum on the grounds that they feared political persecution 
by contrast the lawsuit said half or more of the applicants 
from such countries as afghanistan poland and nicaragua were 
granted asylum 
the lawsuit said the disproportional percentages plainly favored 
refugees fleeing countries deemed to be communist 
the plaintiffs said the settlement modified the role of the 
state department by allowing input from other agencies in each 
case 
the state department will now declare that its recommendation 
will be only one of several factors to be considered by asylum 
officers the plaintiffs said 
