other new graffitirelated laws will make it an infraction to 
write graffiti on public transit buses or trains and will require 
convicted litterers to be sentenced to picking up litter or 
cleaning up graffiti 
kopp said the california legislature is getting tough on 
graffiti because of the proliferation of scrawls and scribbles in 
public places in urban areas 
last week an 18yearold los angeles man was accused of 
painting the word chaka on 10000 traffic signs utility poles 
buildings and walls in southern california causing about 500000 
in damage 
the new law will allow a judge to suspend for one year the 
drivers license of a person 13 years or older convicted of 
graffitirelated vandalism if a 13 or 14 year old doesnt yet have 
a license the court can delay issuance of the license for a year 
after the teen would otherwise be able to get it 
california allows drivers licenses at age 16 with a parents 
signature 
if the 13 or 14yearold doesnt have another conviction for 
graffiti in a year he or she can ask the court to modify the 
suspension the suspension period can also be cut by one day for 
each hour the convicted person spend cleaning up graffiti from 
public property 
kopp notes that current law allows courts to suspend or delay 
drivers licenses for minors convicted of drug and alcohol crimes 
even if the offenses are not drivingrelated 
the punishment fits the crime and the criminal because 
teenagers prize a drivers license above all else kopp said 
the american civil liberties union and california attorneys for 
criminal justice opposed the bill when it moved through the 
legislature saying it was inappropriate to deny a license for 
conduct unrelated to driving 
more appropriate penalties for these type of minor offenses 
would include cleaning up the graffiti cleaning other public areas 
or working with others in painting murals in public places the 
aclu said in a statement opposing the bill 
thats a lame argument kopp said we do not literally 
tailor the punishment to every crime that is committed we do not 
amputate the pickpockets hand 
</TEXT>
