italy has led efforts to preserve some controls on cultural 
treasures 
holding the european communitys rotating presidency this fall 
gave it the perfect opportunity to press the issue the italians 
soon found the lines firmly drawn in what has been called the 
battle of the haves and have nots 
on italys side are other mediterranean haves like spain and 
greece france which always has tried to keep its art at home 
also has pressed for controls 
britain is the leading advocate of a liberalized art market it 
has less to protect and is a center of the international art 
market 
when talks began in may the two camps were farther apart than 
on monetary unity said an official of the italian foreign 
ministry 
in late november with italys term as president running out 
culture ministers asked the ec executive branch to consult experts 
on devising a system for returning illegally exported treasures 
they also agreed to consider certifying artworks and artifacts 
and tightening controls on art leaving the community 
spain proposed that each item be issued a kind of visa britain 
has said it might consider certification for pieces beyond a 
certain worth but the ministry official said that would not work 
for italy 
a small etruscan vase can be worth only 5 million lire 
4300 but for us the value is much more he said because it 
helps complete the story of a collection found in a particular 
tomb 
robert spengler of the french culture ministry said a small 
government ministry might be required to handle certification 
another suggestion is restricting the scope of what constitutes 
a nations heritage 
on dec 13 the european parliament urged ec nations to use 
bettertrained custom officials and adopt tougher laws on sales of 
art and artifacts it also said member nations shouild respect each 
others laws on the subject 
those laws vary widely 
in italy anything unearthed of archaeological interest becomes 
state property 
if a stone lid of an etruscan sarcophagus turns up in holland 
can the owner be forced to give it back especially if he can prove 
he brought it in good faith from a reputable dealer would it all 
end up at the world court 
alessandra melucco of the central institute of restoration in 
rome said other countries had little sympathy for italy given its 
failure to protect excavations and museums adequately 
a superintendent of art in naples in desperation ordered a 
sculptured 15thcentury church entrance walled up this fall soon 
after it was restored he said that was the only way to keep 
vandals and thieves from striking again 
romes archaeology superintendent adriano la regina thinks 
1993 might not be so bad 
its better that objects are displayed in a museum wherever 
it is in the world than to stay in our storerooms on the 
theoretical pretext that they must be studied while nobody studies 
them he said at a forum sponsored by archeo an italian 
archaeology magazine 
after years of talk parliament approved funds this year for an 
ambitious inventory of italys cultural riches police recall 
countless thefts in which the museum or church did not have a photo 
that might aid in recovery 
baldassare conticello superintendent at pompeii said at the 
forum 
if an object is stolen and you can prove it in the end it 
will return since theft is covered by legislation of all nations 
but only a few producer states such as us greece turkey and 
cyprus have laws covering wealth thats underground 
