<TEXT>
it may not be as easy as it used to be to slow 
or reverse an economic decline 
recessions arent necessarily alike and what works on one might 
not on another like strains of flu they may vary vastly from 
their predecessors 
dealing with this one may be a particularly onerous task and 
the biggest problem already has been hinted at it is the poor 
financial condition of the banks themselves and their desire to 
keep matters from getting even worse 
while the federal reserve cut the discount rate or the rate at 
which the commercial banks borrow money from the central bank 
those banks seem less inclined than before to pass on those savings 
to borrowers 
that attitude could mess up the feds plans in fact to some 
extent it already has while the fed has lowered since summer by a 
full percentage point the overnight rate banks charge each other 
the banks havent lowered their rates to customers 
the entire idea of an easier federal reserve policy lowering 
interest rates or expanding the money supply is to spur 
commercial interaction by pumping money through the banks into the 
economy 
that is the expected remedy the routine antidote the aspirin 
for treating dangerous economic slides which the current one has 
become but if the banks let the buck stop with them wouldbe 
users of that money remain frustrated 
what makes this recession unlike many others according to those 
who have studied it is that it is primarily debtinduced much of 
that debt is owed to banks the banks cant collect it has put 
them in a dangerous position 
rather than pass on savings to customers therefore they have 
shown a tendency to hoard what funds they have they are also 
retrenching writing off billions of dollars of loans and closing 
many of their lending operations 
rather than putting money out in the form of loans they are 
trying to get rid of the loans they already have in many 
instances loans not written off entirely are packaged for sale at 
huge discounts just to get rid of them 
loans and customers got the banks into trouble they are licking 
their wounds they are declaring their primary goal now is 1 
survival and 2 clearing the books for the next upturn in which 
they vow to be more prudent 
the prime rate at major banks has been at 10 percent all year 
long and there isnt likely to be any rush to lower it 
substantially 
the earliest indication from a midwest bank is for a 
onequarter point drop which certainly doesnt qualify as 
dramatic except that any decline is rare these days 
creditstarved customers arent likely to leap at such a cut 
in fact those to whom the prime doesnt even apply 
homeowners for example might see more immediate results 
mortgage rates often are tied to government securities prices not 
to bank attitudes and could fall sharply 
that aspect of the feds easier money policy by itself could 
have a very meaningful consequence for the economy many homeowners 
are strapped and mortgage delinquencies are rising those with 
variable rates especially those with mortgages up for their 
periodic review could find quick relief 
the psychological factor also is important for many months the 
fed had steadfastly declined to let up on its tight money policies 
presumably because it considered inflation its no 1 enemy 
now that relief has finally come it may generate buying and 
selling activity among those individuals and companies that had 
been on the sidelines just the psychological attitude could be 
enough to produce some action 
thats how economies move ahead one positive step leading to 
another but dont rely too heavily on the banks its unlikely 
that theyll be the ones to step out ahead of the pack 
