george what should i do should i make this gangster movie or 
shouldnt i francis ford coppola speaking to george lucas in 
1970 
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
francis ford coppola is working around the 
clock pushing himself and his editors to get the latest 
godfather film into theaters by christmas he insists a spring 
release would be better but paramount pictures eyeing the 
deadline for the academy awards wants it out before the end of the 
year 
the movie is screened in san francisco and the projector breaks 
down four times four days later when the film is seen in seattle 
several scenes have been cut and many others added audience 
response is mixed 
the time is december 1974 and as a weary assistant gazes at a 
preview card he lets out an audible groan i hope there will be 
no godfather part iii responds the director so do i 
but its happening again coppola frantically editing paramount 
executives nervously waiting stories about onset blowups and 
lastminute switchesendless curiosity over this most lavish of 
christmas presents 
a new godfather film is hollywoods equivalent to a world 
tour by the rolling stones and its aura of money and power is 
something the corleones would have appreciated the two 
godfather movies have grossed 800 million and won nine academy 
awards between them 
but thats industry talk to moviegoers the godfather means 
brando and duvall pacino and de niro a bloodied horse head and a 
brotherly kiss on new years eve weddings and christenings death 
in a tomato garden bullets ripping through james caan at a toll 
booth 
to the artists it means fame revitalized careers marlon 
brando was washed up al pacino was an unknown stage performer 
coppola was a failed director hired because hed work cheap 
the stakes for the godfather part iii are enormous the 
budget reportedly topped 50 million and a flop could spell 
financial ruin for coppola he and his production company filed for 
bankruptcy protection from creditors during shooting listing 
assets of 222 million and debts of 289 million 
also paramount has struggled this year ghost was an 
enormous hit but both the two jakes and another 48 hrs 
flopped if critics dont take to the new godfather the studio 
could be shut out from the academy awards as it just was by the 
new york and los angeles film critics associations which both 
named another mafia movie goodfellas as best picture 
coppola has compared the corleones to the kennedys tragic 
american dynasties people care about vito sonny michael and 
connie 
mario puzos the godfather came out in 1969 to mixed 
reviews and with complaints from the italianamerican civil rights 
league that the book reinforced stereotypes 
but the novel quickly topped the new york times bestseller 
list and within two years of its first printing 10 million copies 
had been purchased puzo the son of illiterate italian immigrants 
sold the film rights to paramount for 85000 
 
coppola oh yeah let me tell you something about coppola 
coppola would make a great producer you know hes a hustler hes 
got all this talk and chachacha but hes no director 
producer albert ruddy before making the godfather 
 
paramount wanted a lowbudget film an easy profitmaker and 
envisioned a christmas 1971 release ruddy who had worked on tvs 
hogans heroes was assigned to produce for director he 
sought peter yates bullitt who declined and then 
costagavras z who also said no 
ruddy then called on coppola a 32yearold director whose last 
two films had bombed paramount burned by such bigbudget failures 
as catch 22 and paint your wagon needed someone it could 
control also as ruddy noted coppola was an italian who knew 
the way these men ate their food kissed each other talked 
coppola deeply in debt reluctantly accepted the budget was to 
come in under 2 million 
 
i assure you that marlon brando will never appear in this 
film paramount president stanley jaffe 
 
puzo and coppola worked on a screenplay and the director began 
casting caan an old friend of coppolas who had appeared in the 
directors the rain people was quickly chosen to play sonny 
corleone robert duvall also in the rain people was an easy 
choice for consigliere tom hagen 
for michael corleone paramount insisted on a star preferably 
robert redford or warren beatty coppola had his eyes on al pacino 
an offbroadway actor of silician descent the studio objected 
pacinos screen tests were poor he was too short too 
inexperienced and ironically looked too italian but the director 
wouldnt budge and paramount anxious to get shooting under way 
gave in 
the casting of family patriarch vito corleone could only be 
compared to finding the perfect scarlett coppola interviewed every 
old italian actor he could find no one was good enough 
age ruddy and coppola decided didnt matter they simply 
needed a great actor they considered sir laurence olivier but he 
was too ill they also considered brando who puzo had in mind when 
he wrote the character 
the brooding star of a streetcar named desire and on the 
waterfront was then 47 and better at emptying studio coffers than 
filling them it had been years since he had had a hit and budgets 
had soared for his last movies reportedly because of onset battles 
between brando and his directors 
executives wanted nothing to do with him coppola persisted 
paramount agreed to give him a chance but set three conditions 
one brando would receive no salary only a percentage two the 
actor had to guarantee with his own money that he would not cause 
the film to go over budget three he would have to take a screen 
test something he was as likely to do as submit to an interview 
brando agreed to all three for his screen test the actor put 
on a fake mustache slicked back his hair with shoe polish and 
stuffed kleenex in his mouth he got the part 
some italian actors protested the casting of nonitalians 
brando caan and duvall and the iacrl proved as demanding as 
paramount it staged a rally hosted by frank sinatra at madison 
square garden to raise funds to stop the film threatened labor 
disruptions on the set and insisted there was no such thing as the 
mafia 
ruddy promised to keep the words mafia and cosa nostra 
out of the film the words are back in for the godfather part 
iii he also agreed to attend a testimonial dinner hire league 
members as bit players and extras and donate new yorks 
openingnight box office to the leagues hospital fund 
with publicity building and coppolas wheels turning the budget 
was increased to 62 million 
