<TEXT>
filming started march 29 1971 coppola had requested an 80day 
shooting schedule but paramount would only give him 53 with time 
so short scenes were rushed and the dailies came out poorly it 
was rumored coppola would be replaced by elia kazan who had twice 
directed brando the actor helped put an end to such talk by 
insisting he would stop working if coppola was fired 
director of photography gordon willis frustrated with coppolas 
inexperience walked off the set at one point crew members mocked 
talia shire coppolas sister as incompetent the directors 
obsession with retakes drove everyone crazy and a rebellious 
paramount editor was fired 
at first everybody was so uptight francis was a wreck and 
pacino looked like he was going to die said caan who helped 
lighten the mood by cracking jokes with duvall and mooning brando 
on the set 
shooting fell behind schedule and the release date was pushed 
back to easter 1972 the final budget approached 7 million 
the finished movie ran for three hours and stayed that way 
despite complaints from the studio it was first seen in late 
february and most exhibitors who saw it were unimpressed 
on march 11 1972 the godfather opened in new york and all 
was forgiven critics raved and fans poured in there were 
godfather games and godfather soundtracks shouts of make 
him an offer you cant refuse the corleone way of doing 
business were heard from playgrounds to advertising offices 
it was one of those rare films in which every shot seemed to 
have been lovingly crafted the simplest dialogue took on 
additional meaning and even the most minor character had depth and 
personality 
brando had the most memorable role but pacinos michael was the 
center of the movie all the horror and beauty of the godfather 
can be seen in his transformation from an awkward college graduate 
to a cool ruthless mob boss becoming more confident and skillful 
on the outside as his soul burns inside 
michael corleone is one of hollywoods great tragic figures his 
rise and fall comparable to orson welles charles foster kane in 
citizen kane and broderick crawfords willie stark in all the 
kings men 
and like the maltese falcon the godfather had plenty 
to say about the stuff that dreams are made of the films final 
shot a door closing on diane keaton as pacino and associates 
scheme for the future recalls the conclusion of the maltese 
falcon a closeup of elevator doors closing on mary astor as the 
police take her away 
the following march brando won an oscar for best actor and the 
movie won best picture and best screenplay four months later 
paramount announced a sequel with coppola to write and direct 
the godfather part ii alternates between chronicling vitos 
early years and michael in middle age pacino duvall keaton and 
shire returned caan who had been murdered in the first film 
appeared in a flashback sequence brando was not in the sequel 
paramount was furious at him for turning down the oscar in protest 
of hollywoods treatment of american indians and the two sides 
couldnt agree to terms 
to play the young vito corleone coppola selected robert de 
niro who had attracted considerable attention for his role as a 
dying baseball player in bang the drum slowly willis 
apparently thinking more highly of the director was behind the 
cameras 
shooting began in september 1973 and dragged on for eight 
months the budget was a cool 13 million more than double what it 
was supposed to cost 
 
my father assured him either his brains or his signature would 
be on the contract michael corleone explaining how vito 
helped a singer to get a nightclub owner to release him from a 
contract 
 
the godfather part ii another threehour job was released 
in december and reviews were mixed 
still interest was strong enough to bring in millions at the 
box office and six oscars including best film best director 
best screenplay best supporting actor de niro and best score to 
coppolas father carmine 
paramount was already considering the next godfather film 
with or without the troublesome director 
while coppola floundered churning out such flops as rumble 
fish and one from the heart the studio plotted in 1977 
charles bludhorn chairman of gulf amp western industries 
paramounts parent company met with director richard brooks 
blackboard jungle and gave him a 53page treatment for the 
godfather iii brooks wasnt interested 
bludhorn collaborated on a script with puzo novelist vincent 
patrick who wrote the pope of greenwich village and dean 
reisner of dirty harry fame took a shot at it john travolta 
was going to star or maybe sylvester stallone 
in 1988 rumors circulated that coppola was in italy working on 
could it be the godfather part iii a year later they 
were confirmed coppola was back so were pacino keaton and shire 
willis was there too as was carmine coppola for the score 
 
i could make five failures five pictures nobody liked and 
id still be the guy who directed the godfather francis ford 
coppola 
 
andy garcia who plays sonnys outofwedlock son seem the 
best bet to come out a winner with the new movie to do a 
pacino and become a major star pacino and keaton are 
established actors reenacting familiar roles 
sofia coppola the directors daughter is a risk an 
inexperienced actress she was a lastminute substitute for winona 
ryder and has a key role as michaels daughter and garcias love 
interest so far reaction to her performance has been negative 
then theres the director himself beyond all the talk of money 
and awards the saga of the corleones is also the saga of coppola 
the godfather is an accidental classic but was that film just 
a fluke for coppola does he have anything left to say about the 
corleones 
the artists worst fear is that hell be exposed as a sham 
coppola said back in 1975 ive heard it from actors directors 
everyone deep down were all living with the notion that our 
success is beyond our ability 
