a slogan used by quaker oats co to advertise its 
gatorade sports drink infringes on a small companys trademark a 
federal judge has ruled 
us district judge prentice marshall ordered quaker to pay 
247 million in damages to sands taylor amp woods of norwich vt 
for using the phrase thirst aid in the slogan 
sands taylor amp woods operates a soft drink mix company and a 
soda shop 
ron bottrell a spokesman for quaker oats would not comment 
immediately on the ruling 
quaker has used thirst aid on gatorade bottles and in its 
advertising jingles since 1984 bottrell said 
gatorade has been on the market since 1967 primarily used by 
athletes or those performing strenuous exercise it is designed to 
replenish the fluids and electrolytes lost in high heat or through 
exercise 
