<TEXT>
the us economy was still growing at a weak 
14 percent annual rate from july through september the government 
said today but most economists believe it since has slipped into a 
recession 
the commerce department reported its final estimate of the 
thirdquarter gross national product was even slower than its 
initial estimates it first said in october that the gnp had inched 
up 18 percent but revised that downward to 17 percent last month 
in another report the department said housing starts jumped 93 
percent in november their first increase in 10 months but the 
gain was due entirely to a rebound in multifamily starts as 
singlefamily building fell to a level unmatched since the 198182 
recession 
the federal reserve board noted the weakness in the economy 
tuesday when it lowered the discount rate from 7 percent to 65 
percent effective today to stimulate growth and ease the severity 
of any contraction 
but most economists say it will take months before the effects 
of a lower rate work their way through the economy the rate is the 
interest the fed charges on loans to banks and other financial 
institutions 
even bush administration officials while avoiding the use of 
the word recession agree the economy is weakening earlier 
this week treasury secretary nicholas f brady admitted it is 
experiencing a significant slowdown that is likely to persist 
through early 1991 
surveys of private economists and professional forecasters show 
that most believe the economy actually is contracting and will 
continue to deteriorate into next year 
they contend the economy was stumbling along the rim of a 
recession before the aug 2 iraqi invasion of kuwait and that the 
subsequent oilprice shock shoved it over the edge 
a recession generally is defined as two consecutive declines in 
the gnp the nations total output of goods and services and its 
broadest measure of economic health 
it grew at an anemic 17 percent annual rate during the first 
quarter but slowed to an a barely perceptible 04 percent rate in 
the second 
the department also reported that a gnp measure of inflation 
rose at an annual rate of 42 percent it had been revised to 42 
percent last month after the department initially said it had risen 
41 percent 
in its housing report the department said starts of new homes 
and apartments totaled a seasonally adjusted 113 million units 
following a 66 percent drop in october it was the first increase 
since a 232 percent gain last january 
contributing most to the downward revision in the gnp was a 
slower gain in consumer spending and a wider trade deficit than 
first estimated 
consumer spending rose just 27 percent rather than the 32 
percent reported last month the trade deficit was 19 billion 
compared to a 500 million gap in last months estimate 
the largest upward revision was in government spending up 12 
percent rather than 06 percent as reported last month 
business investment advanced 89 percent while housing fell 198 
percent during the quarter business inventories dropped 48 
billion 
the changes meant the total gnp was growing at an annual rate of 
417 trillion in the third quarter when adjusted for inflation 
that was a gain of 15 billion over the second quarter 
the gnp would need to increase 10 percent in the current 
quarter to meet the administrations 07 percent growth estimate 
for the year 
although most economist agree the economy has slipped into a 
recession they disagree over how negative economic growth will be 
and how long the downturn will last and most hedge their 
predictions on the outcome of the persian gulf crisis 
surveys indicate most economists believe the recession began in 
the current quarter and will end by april 
a december survey of 30 professional forecasters by the federal 
reserve bank of philadelphia shows a consensus of the participants 
project the economy to decline at annual rates of about 13 percent 
in the current quarter and 09 percent in the first quarter of 1991 
before inching ahead again in the second 
the consensus forecast of 52 prominent economists surveyed by 
blue chip economic indicators this month finds an identical 
projection 
nevertheless individual forecasts vary widely with some 
analysts saying the economy is in worse shape than the consensus 
and others contending it is in better 
analysts at mitsubishi bank in new york for instance say 
economic growth is dropping at a 25 percent rate economists at 
merrill lynch capital markets in new york say the gnp is declining 
at a 3 percent rate this quarter fuji securities in chicago say 
the economy will decline by 30 percent to 40 percent from october 
through december 
the surveys consensus also shows the economy resuming growth in 
the second quarter but again this view is not unanimous 
the merrill lynch economists for instance say they believe a 
recovery can begin sometime in the second half of 1991 
economists at levy economic forecasts in chappaqua ny also 
forecast the recession itself will end in late 1991 but they 
contend the recession marks the beginning of a contained 
depression caused by overinvestment and that the resulting 
overbuilding and excess capacity will take years to absorb 
</TEXT>
