<TEXT>
southland corps emergence from bankruptcy court 
proceedings may be delayed by a second creditors vote on a 
prepackaged reorganization plan 
us bankruptcy judge harold abramson said tuesday he may order 
creditors to vote again on the plan the company filed in october 
when it sought protection from its creditors under chapter 11 of 
the federal bankruptcy laws 
southland the dallasbased owner of the 7eleven convenience 
store chain put the restructuring plan to a vote just before the 
bankruptcy filing bondholders who oppose the package claim 
southland did not allow sufficient time for a fair vote they also 
claim some ballots were miscounted 
i am prepared to hold that the vote doesnt comply with the 
law abramson said during the second day of testimony 
southland which had sales of almost 8 billion last year said 
it was overwhelmed by the debt left from its 49 billion leveraged 
buyout in 1987 
the company has been struggling under heavy interest payments 
brought on by the buyout which was announced before the oct 19 
1987 stock market crash but financed after it 
the bankruptcy filing listed 253 billion in assets and 338 
billion in liabilities 
southland first proposed a restructuring last march when it 
announced the sale of most of the company to itoyokado co ltd 
and seveneleven japan co ltd its japanese affiliates 
the buyers would provide 430 million in cash for stock in the 
reorganized company 
that amounts to 70 percent of the reorganized southland 
creditors would get 25 percent and the companys founders the 
thompson family of dallas would get 5 percent under the 
prepackaged plan 
in a prepackaged filing most creditors have approved a 
reorganization plan before a company enters bankruptcy if a judge 
approves the terms of the plan are then imposed on the dissenting 
creditors proponents say the speedier process assures a fairer 
deal for more creditors 
southland operates approximately 6900 7eleven stores and other 
convenience outlets in the united states and canada with another 
6000 stores in the united states and 21 other countries run by 
licensees of which seveneleven japan is the largest 
</TEXT>
