grain and soybean futures prices were lower in 
early trading today on the chicago board of trade 
the market opened lower on news that officials of the us 
agriculture department and the soviet union meeting in london on 
tuesday failed to agree on implementation of the export credit 
program said victor lespinasse an analyst with dean witter 
reynolds inc in chicago among the issues in dispute is how grains 
will be shipped to the soviet union 
news that the soviets bought 266500 metric tons of corn is 
expected to weigh on corn futures corn rallied earlier this week 
on rumors of a sale of up to 600000 metric tons 
sluggish export demand for wheat and soybeans is expected to 
weigh on those futures 
in early trading wheat was cent lower to cent higher with 
the contract for delivery in december at 251 a bushel corn was 
cent to 1 cents lower with december at 224 a bushel oats were 
cent lower with march at 114 a bushel soybeans were 1 cent to 
3 cents lower with january at 580 a bushel 
