<DOCNO> AP901219-0232 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
credit boeing for the soft landing 
recessions usually hit this area harder than elsewhere but this 
time economists say the good fortune of the boeing co should 
cushion seattle and much of washington state from the economic 
downturn of the rest of the country 
in a state where a superheated economy produced an average 
annual job growth of 5 percent since 1985 economists are 
forecasting that things might return to normal 
economically the late 1980s were kind to seattle real estate 
values soared in a city considered by many to be among the most 
livable jobs were so plentiful that fastfood joints offered 725 
an hour for flipping burgers developers rebuilt the citys skyline 
with more than a dozen major buildings 
much of that prosperity can be attributed to boeing which has 
104700 workers in washington and accounts for one out of every six 
jobs directly or indirectly in the state 
by late december boeing had received 466 billion in new 
commercial jet business for 1990 approaching a sixth record year 
of orders planes ordered three or four years ago are rolling off 
assembly lines at a rate of better than one a day 
in november however state officials acknowledged that the 
recession gripping much of the country had spread mildly to 
washington state economist chang mook sohn forecasts a net loss of 
10000 nonfarm jobs statewide in the first half of 1991 about 5 
percent of the 21 million member workforce 
in seattle a real estate market that had seen home prices climb 
60 percent to 70 percent from 1987 to 1989 returned to normal as 
too many homes were put up for sale for prices too few buyers could 
afford 
construction also declined with some commercial developers 
delaying projects and complaining about an overbuilt downtown weak 
manufacturing and construction in turn have hurt services the 
retailwholesale trade and finance sectors sohn said 
what happened again sohn and other economists look to boeing 
from 1983 to 1989 boeings employment in this area exploded 
from 58000 to 106000 37 percent of all jobs created in 
washington during that period were with the planemaker 
it was the main force behind the rapid immigration to the 
state and the main force behind the housing boom that resulted 
said douglas pedersen vice president and chief economist for 
security pacific bank of washington 
boeings employment peaked in 1989 as commercial production 
became more efficient and defense cuts threatened government 
projects while the growth in aerospace jobs appears over for now 
sohn says boeings employment isnt likely to fall much further 
one of the big differences between the current downturn and 
previous recessions sohn said is the role of the aerospace 
industry in the past a slowdown in planemaking was an advance 
symptom of a recession and tended to pull down washingtons 
economy 
aerospace works this time is a buffer rather than a 
destabilizing force he said 
the recession of the early 80s was magnified here by boeing 
laying off 22000 employees as orders and deliveries of aircraft 
fell 
in 1982 106 aircraft were ordered and 176 were delivered as 
1990 drew to a close boeings orders already had reached 517 
airplanes and it had delivered at least 364 
it has a firm backlog of at least 1850 planes and hundreds more 
options for purchases and is booking delivery dates past the turn 
of the century 
the region isnt without its worries though the timber 
industry for example is hurting from a slump in homebuilding and 
higher log prices 
the home construction slowdown also has hit here but again not 
as hard as elsewhere 
statewide housing starts for 1990 total 43600 about 38 
percent fewer than 1989 pedersen says commercial construction 
also is lagging 
theres very little new building under way and little 
likelihood of more building in the next few years said jon 
runstad president and chief executive officer of wright runstad a 
major seattle developer 
