chinas first computerized stock market opened 
wednesday in shanghai with almost no stocks for sale 
instead government bonds are the main offering and even their 
sale will be tightly restricted 
the new shanghai securities exchange which opened with great 
fanfare falls far short of what economic reformers envisioned 
several years ago when they proposed setting up a nationwide tock 
market 
the exchange listed only seven stocks on opening day reflecting 
the governments fear of allowing financial speculation 
authorities also are unenthusiastic about stocks because they 
transfer ownership of companies from state hands to the private 
sector 
the market concluded 93 transactions involving a total of 1029 
million yuan worth about 198 million on its first day the 
official news agency xinhua said 
it said more than 500 people attended an opening ceremony 
presided over by shanghai mayor zhu rongji widely regarded as an 
economic reformer 
chinese with cash to invest have demonstrated a keen interest in 
buying securities especially stocks but the government has not 
made it easy for them 
until shanghais market opened they had to keep track of 
differing prices at unlinked trading counters at various shanghai 
banks most counters were open only a few days a week 
