<TEXT>
the decision by the federal reserve to reduce its discount rate 
helped boost the price of gold and silver wednesday on new yorks 
commodity exchange 
on other markets grain and soybeans were sharply lower 
livestock and pork futures were mixed and energy futures gained 
tuesdays cut in the discount rate means the federal government 
is trying to stimulate the economy said peter cardillo director 
of commodities research at jesup josephthal amp co inc 
the lowering of the discount rate particularly helped silver and 
platinum futures which had been in a free fall due to concerns 
about the economy 
silver and platinum depend solely on economic conditions 
cardillo said if the economy can be lifted then obviously both 
metals will do better because of lower interest rates 
gold traded higher on renewed fears of war in the persian gulf 
those fears were rekindled by iraqi rhetoric following the european 
communitys refusal to meat with iraqs foreign minister tariq 
aziz 
also contributing to tensions were reports iraq is adding to its 
forces in kuwait as well as a planned meeting between saudi 
arabian officials and us defense secretary richard cheney and 
gen colin powell chairman of the joint chiefs of staff 
gold settled 950 to 1010 higher with the contract for 
delivery in february at 38800 a troy ounce silver was 132 cents 
to 141 cents higher with december at 4095 a troy ounce platinum 
was 50 to 770 higher with december at 41640 a troy ounce 
grain and soybean futures were lower on the chicago board of 
trade as export trade continued to lag behind expectations 
helping to push prices lower was news that us and soviet 
officials tuesday failed to agree on terms of the 500 million to 
1 billion export credit offer made by the united states the 
soviet union reportedly wants the credit offer to include the cost 
of shipping farm products to the ussr a condition the united 
states is reluctant to agree to 
analysts said if the cost of shipping is included it would 
leave the soviets with less money to purchase grain 
soybean futures were heavily pressured by word of a major 
purchase of south american soybean meal by the soviet union 
so much attention is being paid the lack of business from the 
soviet union that people are ignoring the fact sales to our 
traditional customers taiwan south korean and japan are 
down said analyst joel karlin of research department inc in 
chicago adding that those countries are buying from china which 
had a record crop 
they dont feel the pressure to buy us grains as they have 
felt in the past karlin said 
wheat was cent to 4 cents lower with december at 247 a 
bushel corn was 1 cent to 3 cents lower with december at 224 a 
bushel oats were 1 cent to 1 cents lower with december at 105 
a bushel soybeans were 5 cents to 7 cents lower with january at 
576 a bushel 
energy futures moved higher in quiet trading on the new york 
mercantile exchange 
robert baker an analyst with prudentialbache securities inc 
said the markets strength came from a stronger feeling that war 
eventually will erupt in the middle east 
light sweet crude was 1 cent to 34 cents higher with february at 
2693 a barrel heating oil was 70 cent to 217 cents higher with 
january at 7784 a gallon unleaded gasoline was 41 cent to 70 
cent higher with january at 6742 cents a gallon natural gas was 
064 cent lower to 010 cent higher with january at 2046 per 
1000 cubic feet 
livestock futures were lower and pork futures higher on the 
chicago mercantile exchange with cattle prices pressured by lower 
cash prices and reduced retail beef demand 
frozen pork bellies were up the 2cent limit as traders took 
advantage of the slide in prices in recent trading sessions to 
pocket profits 
live cattle were 12 cent to 45 cent lower with december at 
8050 cents a pound feeder cattle were 25 cent to 50 cent lower 
with january at 8875 cents a pound live hogs were 15 cent to 50 
cent lower with february at 4960 cents a pound frozen pork 
bellies were 188 cents to 2 cents lower with february at 6410 
cents a pound 
