<TEXT>
continental airlines received a federal 
bankruptcy judges approval wednesday to sell its prized 
seattletokyo route to healthy rival american airlines for 150 
million 
the sale was one of a number of actions sanctioned by judge 
helen balick she is overseeing the reorganization of the airline 
that sought refuge from creditors dec 3 because of crushing debts 
and high fuel prices incited by the persian gulf crisis 
the houstonbased airline which like many companies is 
incorporated in delaware is among the weaker commercial carriers 
in an industry thats under enormous pressure from a slumping 
economy that has discouraged air travel 
continental had wanted to retain the seattletokyo route it is 
one of the most profitable because of burgeoning business between 
the west coast and asia 
but as the airlines financial problems grew more acute 
management decided the route was expendable and the cash provided 
from a sale could be put to better use 
continental officials said the proceeds from the sale which was 
first announced shortly after the airline sought bankruptcy 
protection would be used to buy new aircraft it has ordered 
for american the route provides a critical gateway to the 
pacific where the airline will compete directly with united 
airlines which now dominates usasian air travel 
the route sale still requires transportation department 
approval 
in other actions wednesday balick also approved some 
preliminary payments to contractors refurbishing continentals 
terminal at new yorks laguardia airport 
she agreed to hold a hearing dec 28 on the airlines request 
for permission to pay some tour operators and travel agents 
</TEXT>
