fourteen ohio congressmen on wednesday urged 
federal regulators to scrutinize american telephone amp telegraph 
cos 61 billion takeover bid for ncr corp 
the legislators claim the merger could be anticompetitive and 
result in higher telephone rates 
if the merger does not work the costs of repaying the 6 
billion which atampt is borrowing is likely to be borne by 
longdistance telephone consumers the congressmen said in a 
letter to the federal communications commission 
in their letter to attorney general richard thornburgh the 
lawmakers warned that the merger could give atampt the potential to 
develop an unfair advantage in the financial services sector 
us rep tony hall the democrat who spearheaded the effort 
said the letters are part of a counterstrike by the delegation to 
block the takeover which is strongly opposed by local ohio 
government and business leaders 
also signing the letters were democratic reps louis stokes 
douglas applegate thomas luken edward feighan marcy kaptur mary 
rose oakar donald pease and james traficant and republican reps 
michael oxley bob mcewen michael dewine and paul gillmor rep 
john kasich a republican signed only the letter the justice 
department 
there are 21 congressional districts in ohio 
atampts 90pershare cash tender offer was rejected unanimously 
by ncrs board 
atampt has said it will try to persuade stockholders to call a 
special meeting and seek to oust the dayton ohiobased computer 
makers board of directors 
