<TEXT>
union workers at smallengine and lock maker 
briggs amp stratton corp voted wednesday to accept wage cuts and 
other concessions to keep their jobs from being transferred south 
members of allied industrial workers local 232 which represents 
some 6000 workers at briggs plants in milwaukee voted 2512 to 
2246 to accept the concessions 
the concessions include a 2 an hour wage cut for the 1200 
workers in the small engine division increased health insurance 
costs for workers and elimination of a companywide profit sharing 
program 
in exchange for the concessions the company promised not to 
move any of its engine or lock work out of its suburban milwaukee 
plant at least until july 1994 
briggs had threatened to move the jobs to plants in kentucky or 
indiana if the milwaukee workers did not accept the wage cuts 
we were very disappointed about it they were holding a club 
above our members heads we accepted it because the priority is 
job security local 232 president dick crofter said 
briggs chief executive frederick p stratton issued a brief 
statement after the union vote indicating the company hopes to 
improve relations with the union 
workers in the smallengine division average about 14 an hour 
according to figures supplied by local 232 of the allied industrial 
workers those employees also receive fringe benefits valued at 
about 575 an hour 
a southern facility would eliminate transportation costs to 
briggs customers many of whom are now in the south officials 
said 
